04219nam a22005295i 9780520951730DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209517307 a10.1525/97805209517302doi  a(DE-B1597)648935  a(OCoLC)1408681642  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aART0150302bisacsh1 aGourianova, Nina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAesthetics of Anarchy :bArt and Ideology in the Early Russian Avant-Garde /cNina Gourianova; ed. by Nina Gurianova. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b68 scattered halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. The Russian Avant-Garde and the Aesthetics of Anarchy -- tPart I: Movements and Ideas -- t1. The Aesthetics of Anarchy: Definitions -- t2. Ideas: Bakunin, Tolstoy, and the Russian Anarchists -- t3. Movements: Futurisms and the Principle of Freedom -- tPart II: Poetics -- t4. A Game in Hell: The Poetics of Chance and Play -- t5. Victory over the Sun and the Theater of Alogism -- t6. Deconstructing the Canon: Russian Futurist Books -- tPart III: Locating the Avant-Garde’s Social Stance -- t7. The “Social Test”: The Avant-Garde and the GreatWar -- t8. The Suprematist Party -- tPart IV: Politics -- t9. Art, Creativity, and Anarkhiia -- t10. The Last Revolt: Politics of the Left Federation -- t11. The Avant-Garde and Ideology -- tConclusion. The Historical Paradigm: The Avant-Gardes and Revolution -- tNotes -- tList of Illustrations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this groundbreaking study, Nina Gurianova identifies the early Russian avant-garde (1910-1918) as a distinctive movement in its own right and not a preliminary stage to the Constructivism of the 1920s. Gurianova identifies what she terms an “aesthetics of anarchy”—art-making without rules—that greatly influenced early twentieth-century modernists. Setting the early Russian avant-garde movement firmly within a broader European context, Gurianova draws on a wealth of primary and archival sources by individual writers and artists, Russian theorists, theorizing artists, and German philosophers. Unlike the post-revolutionary avant-garde, which sought to describe the position of the artist in the new social hierarchy, the early Russian avant-garde struggled to overcome the boundaries defining art and to bridge the traditional gap between artist and audience. As it explores the aesthetics embraced by the movement, the book shows how artists transformed literary, theatrical, and performance practices, eroding the traditional boundaries of the visual arts and challenging the conventions of their day.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aArt. 4aEuropean. 7aART / European.2bisacsh1 aGurianova, Nina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026876040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095173040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520951730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520951730/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles